SQL INSERT INTO Statement

The SQL INSERT INTO statement is used to insert new records into a table.
It is the most common way to add new rows of data to a database.

INSERT INTO can be written in two main forms:

Syntax 1: Specify column names
INSERT INTO table_name (column1, column2, column3, ...)
VALUES (value1, value2, value3, ...);

What this does:
This inserts a new row using only the listed columns.
Any columns not specified will use their default values or NULL if allowed.
When to use it:
Use this when you want to insert data into specific columns only.

Syntax 2: Insert values for all columns
INSERT INTO table_name
VALUES (value1, value2, value3, ...);

What this does:
This inserts new rows using values for all columns in the table, in the table's defined order.
When to use it:
Use this when you are providing a complete row and know the correct column order.

