INSERT INTO Example: Insert values for all columns
Here we insert values for ALL the columns of the table, so we omit the column names.
Example:
INSERT INTO Customers
VALUES ('Cardinal', 'Tom B. Erichsen', 'Skagen 21', 'Stavanger', '4006', 'Norway');

What this does:
This query adds a new row to the Customers table.
Because CustomerID is an auto-increment field, the database generates the next CustomerID automatically.
When to use it:
Use this when you are inserting a complete record and the table will fill any auto-generated columns.

Result after inserting this row:
CustomerID  CustomerName  ContactName       Address      City       PostalCode  Country
92          Cardinal      Tom B. Erichsen  Skagen 21    Stavanger  4006        Norway

Important note:
In this example we did not include CustomerID in the VALUES list.
That is valid if CustomerID is defined as an auto-increment column.

Insert Data Only in Specific Columns
Sometimes you only want to insert values into a subset of columns.
Example:
INSERT INTO Customers (CustomerName, City, Country)
VALUES ('Cardinal', 'Stavanger', 'Norway');

What this does:
This query inserts a new row with values for CustomerName, City, and Country only.
Other columns such as ContactName, Address, and PostalCode will be set to NULL or default values.
When to use it:
Use this when you do not have values for every column and want to insert partial data.

Result after inserting this row:
CustomerID  CustomerName  ContactName  Address  City       PostalCode  Country
92          Cardinal      NULL         NULL     Stavanger  NULL        Norway

Tips for inserting specific columns:
- Always list the column names in the same order as the values.
- Do not include columns if you want the database to fill them automatically.

Insert Multiple Rows
To insert more than one row in a single statement, provide multiple value sets separated by commas.
Example:
INSERT INTO Customers (CustomerName, ContactName, Address, City, PostalCode, Country)
VALUES
('Cardinal', 'Tom B. Erichsen', 'Skagen 21', 'Stavanger', '4006', 'Norway'),
('Greasy Burger', 'Per Olsen', 'Gateveien 15', 'Sandnes', '4306', 'Norway'),
('Tasty Tee', 'Finn Egan', 'Streetroad 19B', 'Liverpool', 'L1 0AA', 'UK');

What this does:
This query inserts three new rows into the Customers table in one statement.
When to use it:
Use this to add multiple rows efficiently and reduce the number of separate SQL commands.

Important note:
Make sure each row of values is separated by a comma, and the last row ends with a semicolon.

Result after inserting these rows:
